<a href="javascript:card_browser(57)">Worry</a> x3<br />
Vengeance<br />
Kill Them Now<br />
Can You Protect Me From Yourself?<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(33)">Saruman&#39;s Power</a><br />
<br />
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> READ THE STRAT PLEASE! I KNOW IT&#39;S LONG, BUT IF YOU DON&#39;T READ IT AND REVIEW THE DECK YOU&#39;LL LIKELY MISS THE IDEA!<br />
<br />
Now the first thing you&#39;ll notice about this deck is that it goes against many Fellowship deck building &#39;rules&#39; that are commonly held amongst players:<br />
<br />
*It usually keeps 6+ companions on the table<br />
*It runs more than 4 different cultures<br />
*It isn&#39;t uruk bomb, trust, help, or any other dominant deck type.<br />
*Oh, and it&#39;s OPEN.<br />
<br />
Why you ask? Well for one thing, I&#39;m sick of playing the decks DECIPHER wants me to play, and for another I&#39;ve loved the whole unbound/THREE hunters strat ever since it came out. I think this deck has done a good job of addressing all the concerns such a deck might have, while at the same time being what I intended it to...A FUN competitive deck that&#39;s not supposed to win any medals, but to 1) Smack Grima in the face with his inferiority and 2) Show other players that decks of this nature CAN work, despite Enquea, Grima etc.<br />
<br />
Now I may not have any fancy tourney stats to back this deck up, but I&#39;ve playtested the hell out of it ever since TTT and it&#39;s adapted with BoHD (for the better I found!). <br />
<br />
Now Grima, CC. The thing with him is, with 3 Foul Creations in the deck (that I&#39;d have put in even if Grima DIDN&#39;T exist), I can catch him before he comes out, and if he slips past he&#39;ll either be neutered by a Quick As May Be or two, or will generally prove ineffective given this deck&#39;s &quot;Throw the shimmer at the wall and see what sticks nature&quot;. So what if he sends Gimli with his axe back to your hand? You have plenty other lambs around to make up for it. As for Enquea, it&#39;s the same general idea (minus the Foul Creation), but with Eowyn specifically included to cop him, it evens out pretty much. I mean, all these concepts are NOT 100% fool-proof, but then again...what is in the world of LOTR these days? <br />
<br />
Now enough self-important ranting...onto the strategy...It&#39;s pretty straight-forward, I mean, you all know the unbound hobbit strategy so I&#39;ll spare you the general idea and get to the specifics of the deck...bid 4 (one&#39;s removed with Pip so it&#39;s all good). If you&#39;re first, which is likely for the best (I mean, you CAN cut the opponent off at site two if you go second, it&#39;s just preferable to go first) so you can dump your fellowship cards and ready the onslaught of burdens and trackers.<br />
<br />
It&#39;s so simple to play this deck it&#39;s not even funny. You literally just dump all your fellowship stuff, which may seem like a bad idea, but between the direct damage, discarding hobbits, Eowyn, Sam, and the power of the 3 Hunters this is actually quite easy. The whole point? Keep the hunters alive and the hobbits. The game IS survival with the Fellowship and the hunters are the way to do it. If one getshimmer? That&#39;s okay, there are numerous throw-in companions in this deck that I&#39;ll explain later in detail.<br />
<br />
I guess the thing that needs the most explanation of this deck is the card choices, so here&#39;s why what&#39;s in there is in there...<br />
<br />
Treebeard and Gandalf are your Hobbit retrivers, you sac &#39;em with Warmed Up A Bit and bring &#39;em back. I only run 2 &#39;beards and one Gandalf &#39;cause I don&#39;t want to clog my hand, thus I run A Wizard Is Never Late as it&#39;s like having another of each in the deck (but BETTER!). Gandalf also acts as a sacrficial lamb in that once you&#39;re done discarding the hobbits (which will heal themselves and others if it&#39;s Pip) or you have &#39;beard out (the better of the two hobbit fetchers) he can just eat minions for you until he&#39;s gone.<br />
<br />
Now Eowyn, and Sam run sorta the same as Gandalf in that they DO have key parts to play, but are expendable at the same time. Sam gets rid of your burdens and Eowyn blocks Enquea as best she can. After they&#39;ve done their part they can just eat a minion or two and die. Sam&#39;ll die about the first turn you play him (unless you can finagle him sticking around longer while the hunters kick some ass, thus keeping him around for when you absolutely need him). <br />
<br />
Quick As May Be not only is a great card to help weaken a minion, but to pipeweed-block Grima or Enquea. Now you may ask why I don&#39;t have Baruk Khazad, as it&#39;s a great card to combo with such a strat, but I found in my attempts to make this deck less reliant on one specific culture or companion (and one who&#39;s not exactly made of vitality to drain on cards like this) I opted to drop it. <br />
<br />
I think that does it for the Fellowship, as the rest is very obvious...Hard Choice for healing, BoA &#39;cause Uruks are still huge etc. etc. Oh yeah...the two Gimli&#39;s Axes are because it&#39;s such a HUGE card, especially against wargs. <br />
<br />
Now for the shadow, the strats the same old tracker/worry combo deck that&#39;s been getting more popular. Gollum and Enquea play off the burdens of course, that the Uruks (I added Lurtz &#39;cause he&#39;s huge) add. Corruption&#39;s not really the goal so much as hindrance. I mean, with G and E (ha ha ha, that&#39;s a new one) playing off the burdens that&#39;s dead companions by the barrelful. The Grimas and the Tower Assassin are there to help control the table, by knocking out some pesky allies and comps so I can wreak havoc with my trackers on the leftovers or just plain stop a double-move.<br />
<br />
Now this deck has a weakness to choke, so I added Saruman&#39;s Power to knock out all their No Strangers which is the main problem card for this Shadow.<br />
<br />
Few more things before I go...I run only BBSwords &#39;cause Ugluk&#39;s Sword isn&#39;t as profoundly useful in this deck...Can You Protect Me is basically 2 free burdens or an exhausted &#39;Gorn in most cases, so it made a lot of sense for it to go into this deck. I run 2 Saruman&#39;s Ambition as it can help me cycle fast, and if I&#39;m up against Dauntless Hunter for 2 twilight all my Isengard events that are normally free would cost 1 instead of 2. With the 2 Ambitions I saw no point in multiple Vengeances and/or Kill Them Nows so I put one of each in for variety. <br />
<br />
Anyway, thanks for checking this deck out and I appreciate any constructive reviews I get. :) </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=28364"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=28364" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
